There's a nuance here related to the interplay of security and caching -- as implemented, if you were to have the same callable as a dependency in multiple places with different security schemes, you'd get a repeat of the dependency's arguments in the schema for each different security scheme.

In theory, this could be avoided if there was a way to "merge" all of the relevant security schemes in a way that was equivalent to the list of all distinct schemes that appear for a given dependency. I *think* that this should be possible by basically unioning the list of scopes. But I'm not 100% confident I fully understand the logic there. 

@tiangolo if that is right, I'm happy to work through merging the security scopes; on the other hand, it seems like it might be enough of an edge case to not block on (given the simplicity of this implementation and how much more likely it is to be relevant in practice).

