@BarryThrill, I'd recommend for JWT or OAuth stick only to standard implementations you can reproduce.

IMO the password auth flow is fine when your identity provider and app are the same system. It is common for username and passwords to be base64 encoded in transit through TLS. Once you have retrieved your token you will present it for each subsequent request. The key thing here is that the browser client, api, and IdP should all be your system in this scenario and therefore trusted. So the issued the token doesn't work on other systems anyway, and if you don't want passwords on your system should you really be using the password flow then (or if you can't protect your logs is your system secure either)?

If you want to publish the client on something like Google Play or IOS App Store then you should consider PKCE instead of hard-coded passwords. PKCE requires authorization_code instead of password flow though. The authorization_code would also prevent passwords from being on your system.

